content:
The integral functions $f^{(n)}$ governing the renormalization group flow in an itinerant fermion system are defined as follows:
$f^{(0)}(T)=F_{k}^{\prime}+F_{\epsilon}^{\prime}$ (representing energy and momentum shell contributions to the free energy);
$f^{(2)}(T,\delta)=\frac{2}{\pi}\int_{0}^{1}\frac{d^{d}k}{(2\pi)^{d}}k^{z-2}\coth\left(\frac{k^{z-2}}{2T}\right)\frac{1}{1+(\delta+k^{2})^{2}}+K_{d}\int_{0}^{1}\frac{d\varepsilon}{\pi}\coth\left(\frac{\varepsilon}{2T}\right)\frac{\varepsilon}{\varepsilon^{2}+(\delta+1)^{2}}$;
$f^{(4)}(T,\delta)=\frac{2}{\pi}\int_{0}^{1}\frac{d^{d}k}{(2\pi)^{d}}k^{z-2}\coth\left(\frac{k^{z-2}}{2T}\right)\frac{\delta+k^{2}}{[1^{2}+(\delta+k^{2})^{2}]^{2}} +K_{d}\int_{0}^{1}\frac{d\varepsilon}{\pi}\coth\left(\frac{\varepsilon}{2T}\right)\frac{\varepsilon(\delta+1)}{[\varepsilon^{2}+(\delta+1)^{2}]^{2}}$,
where $K_d$ is the surface area of the $d$-dimensional unit sphere divided by $(2\pi)^d$, $z$ is the dynamic exponent, and the cutoffs for momentum and frequency are normalized to unity.

Substitution of Pb for Hg in the $m=3$ compound, forming $Hg_{1-x}Pb_{x}Ba_{2}Ca_{2}Cu_{3}O_{8+\delta}$, significantly suppresses the pressure-induced $T_{c}$ enhancement compared to the undoped parent compound. Specifically:
      for $x=0.1$, $T_{co}$ peaks at $\sim 151$ K near 10 GPa;
      for $x=0.2$, $T_{co}$ peaks at $\sim 145$ K near 9 GPa and decreases at higher pressures.

