X-ray powder diffraction analysis reveals that the prepared material consists of three distinct crystallographic phases:
  1. A layer-type perovskite-like phase related to the $K_{2}NiF_{4}$ structure with lattice parameters $a=3.79\text{ \AA}$ and $c=13.21\text{ \AA}$;
  2. A cubic phase whose intensity depends on the Barium concentration $x(Ba)$;
  3. A third phase, chemically identified as $CuO$, with a volume fraction greater than $30\%$.

